$A \cup B = \{x: x \in A \text{ and } x \in B\}$
$A \cup B = \{x: x \in A \text{ and } x \notin B\}$
$A \cup B = \{x: x \notin A \text{ and } x \in B\}$
$A \cap B = \{x: x \in A \text{ or } x \in B\}$
$A \cap B = \{x: x \in A \text{ and } x \in B\}$
$A \cap B = \{x: x \in A \text{ and } x \notin B\}$
$A \cap B = \{x: x \notin A \text{ and } x \in B\}$
The difference of sets A and B is the set that consists of all elements in A that are not in B.
The difference of sets A and B is the set that consists of only element in A and B
The difference of sets A and B is the set that involves all elements in A and B
When $Q \cup Q = Q$ and $Q \cap Q = Q$
None of the above (it is the Harmonic series and it is divergent)
